{"title_page": "Th\u00e9odore Gudin", "text_new": "{{Infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL |caption=Th\u00e9odore Gudin, photograph by [[\u00c9tienne Carjat]] (c.1865)}}\n'''Jean Antoine Th\u00e9odore Gudin''' (15 August 1802 - 11 April 1880) was a French [[marine painter]]. Along with [[Louis-Philippe Cr\u00e9pin]], he became one of the first two official [[Peintre de la Marine|Peintres de la Marine]] in 1830.\n\n== Biography ==\nGudin was born in [[Paris]]. Nothing is known of his father and, in his memoirs, he seems to suggest that his mother was a widow who took full responsibility for raising him and his older brother, Jean-Louis  (1799-1823).<ref name=Souvenirs01>B\u00e9raud, ''Souvenirs du Baron Gudin'', pgs. 25-26.</ref>. He was enrolled at a naval school, but quit his studies to go to New York, where he mingled with the [[Bonapartist]]s in exile. In 1819, he joined the [[United States Navy]] and sailed aboard the ''Manchester Packet'', a 250 ton [[brig]].<ref name=\"LFM\">[[Eug\u00e8ne Sue]], In: [https://books.google.fr/books?id=u5FBAAAAcAAJ&hl=fr&pg=PP9#v=onepage&q&f=false ''La France maritime''], edited by Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Gr\u00e9han, Paris, Postel, 1837, Vol. III, pgs.158-160.</ref>.\n\nIn 1822, he returned to Paris and, inspired by his brother (who had become a student of [[Horace Vernet]]) he decided to pursue a career in art and found a position in the studios of [[Anne-Louis Girodet]].<ref name=Souvenirs01/>. He made his debut at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] that same year.<ref>[http://salons.musee-orsay.fr/index/exposant/58661 Base Salons], Paris, ann\u00e9e 1822, mus\u00e9e d'Orsay.</ref>. The following year, he and his brother were involved in a shipwreck on the Seine, from which he escaped. His brother drowned, however, and this affected him deeply for the rest of his life.<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Miroir des spectacles, des lettres, des m\u0153urs et des arts|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6237691k|website=Gallica|language=FR|date=1823-03-07|access-date=2018-12-31|publication-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:BatailleCaplizard.jpg|thumb|300px|left|''[[Battle at The Lizard]]'' (oil on canvas, 1840s)]]\nIn 1824, he had another exhibition at the Salon and won the support of future King [[Louis Philippe I]] with a painting of the ship that had taken him on a visit to America. In 1828, King [[Charles X of France|Charles X]] commissioned him to paint a depiction of Ensign {{ill|Hippolyte Bisson|fr}} who, the year before, had blown up his ship rather than surrender it to pirates. Shortly after, Gudin went with his friend, [[Abel Aubert Dupetit Thouars]], to participate in the [[French conquest of Algeria|Algerian Expedition]], where he made numerous sketches. \n\nUpon his return, he was named a \"Peintre de la Marine\" at the court of Louis Philippe. Over the next few years, he made painting trips to Italy, Switzerland and Russia. He was then created a Baron by the King and commissioned to produce ninety paintings on French naval history for the [[Palace of Versailles]], a monumental task that apparently undermined his health.\n\nHe was named an officer in the [[Legion of Honor]] in 1841<ref name=\"LH\"/>. Following an exhibit in Berlin in 1845, he received the cross ''[[Pour le M\u00e9rite]]''<ref>J. Wagner, ''Der Orden \u201ePour le merite\u201c f\u00fcr Wissenschaft und K\u00fcnste. Die Mitglieder 1842\u20131883'', Gebr. Mann-Verlag, Berlin, 1975.</ref>. In 1844, he married Louise Margaret Hay (1820-1890), daughter of the English General James Hay (1788-1862) and goddaughter of the King. They had three children, including the painter [[Henriette Gudin]]. \n\nDuring the [[French Revolution of 1848]], he divided his time between France and England and remained neutral. However, during the [[French coup d'\u00e9tat of 1851|Coup d'\u00c9tat of 1851]], he came down firmly on the side of the Republicans. In 1857, he was named a Commander in the Legion of Honor.<ref name=\"LH\">{{Base L\u00e9onore|LH/1214/30}}</ref>. \nIn 1865, back in favor with the Bonapartes, he accompanied the Emperor, [[Napol\u00e9on III]], to Algeria and returned by way of [[Tangiers]] on the Imperial [[corvette]] ''[[French ship Cassard (1846)|La Reine Hortense]]''.  \n[[File:Loss of indiaman Kent-Theodore Gudin-MnM 9 OA 34 D-a.png|thumb|300px| ''Loss of the [[Kent (1820 EIC ship)|East indiaman Kent]]'' (1828), [[Paris]], [[mus\u00e9e national de la Marine]]]]\nHe served as Vice-President of the {{ill|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 centrale de sauvetage des naufrag\u00e9s|fr}}<ref>La Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 centrale de sauvetage des naufrag\u00e9s (SCSN), a \u00e9t\u00e9 [http://gatinais.histoire.pagesperso-orange.fr/Rigault_de_Genouilly.htm reconnue d\u2019utilit\u00e9 publique par un d\u00e9cret imp\u00e9rial du 17 novembre 1865]</ref>, which he helped to create in 1864, in memory of his late brother Jean Louis.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k1133832/f707.item.r=gudin%20jean%20louis.zoom Biography of Jean Louis Gudin] @ Gallica BnF</ref>. After the fall of the Empire in 1870, he went into self-imposed exile in England and used the name \"Gordon\". He was able to return to France in 1879, following the death of [[Napol\u00e9on, Prince Imperial|Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte]], and died at [[Boulogne-Billancourt]] in 1880.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* ''Souvenirs du baron Gudin : Peintre de la marine (1820-1870)'', edited by Edmond B\u00e9raud, Plon, (1921) [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6572544v Full text online] @ ''Gallica''\n* Alain Noslier, \"Th\u00e9odore Jean Antoine Gudin : premier peintre officiel de la Marine en 1830\" In, ''Les Cahiers de la vie \u00e0 Cancale'' #30, 2006, pgs.70-79\n* St\u00e9phanie Debuiche, \"Th\u00e9odore Gudin au Mus\u00e9e national de la Marine\" In, ''Neptunia'' #260, 2010, pgs.24-32\n* St\u00e9phanie Debuiche, \"Th\u00e9odore Gudin : de la mer \u00e0 la cour\" In, ''Chasse-mar\u00e9e'' #228, 2010, pgs.60-65\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Th\u00e9odore Gudin}}\n* [http://www.artnet.com/artists/baron-jean-antoine-th\u00e9odore-gudin/ More works by Gudin] @ ArtNet\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gudin, Theodore}}\n\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1880 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n[[Category:19th-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French male painters]]\n[[Category:Peintres de la Marine]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pour le M\u00e9rite (civil class)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Th\u00e9odore Gudin photographie.jpg|thumb|200px|Th\u00e9odore Gudin, photograph by [[\u00c9tienne Carjat]] (c.1865)]]\n'''Jean Antoine Th\u00e9odore Gudin''' (15 August 1802 - 11 April 1880) was a French [[marine painter]]. Along with [[Louis-Philippe Cr\u00e9pin]], he became one of the first two official [[Peintre de la Marine|Peintres de la Marine]] in 1830.\n\n== Biography ==\nGudin was born in [[Paris]]. Nothing is known of his father and, in his memoirs, he seems to suggest that his mother was a widow who took full responsibility for raising him and his older brother, Jean-Louis  (1799-1823).<ref name=Souvenirs01>B\u00e9raud, ''Souvenirs du Baron Gudin'', pgs. 25-26.</ref>. He was enrolled at a naval school, but quit his studies to go to New York, where he mingled with the [[Bonapartist]]s in exile. In 1819, he joined the [[United States Navy]] and sailed aboard the ''Manchester Packet'', a 250 ton [[brig]].<ref name=\"LFM\">[[Eug\u00e8ne Sue]], In: [https://books.google.fr/books?id=u5FBAAAAcAAJ&hl=fr&pg=PP9#v=onepage&q&f=false ''La France maritime''], edited by Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Gr\u00e9han, Paris, Postel, 1837, Vol. III, pgs.158-160.</ref>.\n\nIn 1822, he returned to Paris and, inspired by his brother (who had become a student of [[Horace Vernet]]) he decided to pursue a career in art and found a position in the studios of [[Anne-Louis Girodet]].<ref name=Souvenirs01/>. He made his debut at the [[Salon (Paris)|Salon]] that same year.<ref>[http://salons.musee-orsay.fr/index/exposant/58661 Base Salons], Paris, ann\u00e9e 1822, mus\u00e9e d'Orsay.</ref>. The following year, he and his brother were involved in a shipwreck on the Seine, from which he escaped. His brother drowned, however, and this affected him deeply for the rest of his life.<ref>{{cite web|title=Le Miroir des spectacles, des lettres, des m\u0153urs et des arts|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6237691k|website=Gallica|language=FR|date=1823-03-07|access-date=2018-12-31|publication-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:BatailleCaplizard.jpg|thumb|300px|left|''[[Battle at The Lizard]]'' (oil on canvas, 1840s)]]\nIn 1824, he had another exhibition at the Salon and won the support of future King [[Louis Philippe I]] with a painting of the ship that had taken him on a visit to America. In 1828, King [[Charles X of France|Charles X]] commissioned him to paint a depiction of Ensign {{ill|Hippolyte Bisson|fr}} who, the year before, had blown up his ship rather than surrender it to pirates. Shortly after, Gudin went with his friend, [[Abel Aubert Dupetit Thouars]], to participate in the [[French conquest of Algeria|Algerian Expedition]], where he made numerous sketches. \n\nUpon his return, he was named a \"Peintre de la Marine\" at the court of Louis Philippe. Over the next few years, he made painting trips to Italy, Switzerland and Russia. He was then created a Baron by the King and commissioned to produce ninety paintings on French naval history for the [[Palace of Versailles]], a monumental task that apparently undermined his health.\n\nHe was named an officer in the [[Legion of Honor]] in 1841<ref name=\"LH\"/>. Following an exhibit in Berlin in 1845, he received the cross ''[[Pour le M\u00e9rite]]''<ref>J. Wagner, ''Der Orden \u201ePour le merite\u201c f\u00fcr Wissenschaft und K\u00fcnste. Die Mitglieder 1842\u20131883'', Gebr. Mann-Verlag, Berlin, 1975.</ref>. In 1844, he married Louise Margaret Hay (1820-1890), daughter of the English General James Hay (1788-1862) and goddaughter of the King. They had three children, including the painter [[Henriette Gudin]]. \n\nDuring the [[French Revolution of 1848]], he divided his time between France and England and remained neutral. However, during the [[French coup d'\u00e9tat of 1851|Coup d'\u00c9tat of 1851]], he came down firmly on the side of the Republicans. In 1857, he was named a Commander in the Legion of Honor.<ref name=\"LH\">{{Base L\u00e9onore|LH/1214/30}}</ref>. \nIn 1865, back in favor with the Bonapartes, he accompanied the Emperor, [[Napol\u00e9on III]], to Algeria and returned by way of [[Tangiers]] on the Imperial [[corvette]] ''[[French ship Cassard (1846)|La Reine Hortense]]''.  \n[[File:Loss of indiaman Kent-Theodore Gudin-MnM 9 OA 34 D-a.png|thumb|300px| ''Loss of the [[Kent (1820 EIC ship)|East indiaman Kent]]'' (1828), [[Paris]], [[mus\u00e9e national de la Marine]]]]\nHe served as Vice-President of the {{ill|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 centrale de sauvetage des naufrag\u00e9s|fr}}<ref>La Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 centrale de sauvetage des naufrag\u00e9s (SCSN), a \u00e9t\u00e9 [http://gatinais.histoire.pagesperso-orange.fr/Rigault_de_Genouilly.htm reconnue d\u2019utilit\u00e9 publique par un d\u00e9cret imp\u00e9rial du 17 novembre 1865]</ref>, which he helped to create in 1864, in memory of his late brother Jean Louis.<ref>[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k1133832/f707.item.r=gudin%20jean%20louis.zoom Biography of Jean Louis Gudin] @ Gallica BnF</ref>. After the fall of the Empire in 1870, he went into self-imposed exile in England and used the name \"Gordon\". He was able to return to France in 1879, following the death of [[Napol\u00e9on, Prince Imperial|Louis-Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte]], and died at [[Boulogne-Billancourt]] in 1880.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* ''Souvenirs du baron Gudin : Peintre de la marine (1820-1870)'', edited by Edmond B\u00e9raud, Plon, (1921) [https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6572544v Full text online] @ ''Gallica''\n* Alain Noslier, \"Th\u00e9odore Jean Antoine Gudin : premier peintre officiel de la Marine en 1830\" In, ''Les Cahiers de la vie \u00e0 Cancale'' #30, 2006, pgs.70-79\n* St\u00e9phanie Debuiche, \"Th\u00e9odore Gudin au Mus\u00e9e national de la Marine\" In, ''Neptunia'' #260, 2010, pgs.24-32\n* St\u00e9phanie Debuiche, \"Th\u00e9odore Gudin : de la mer \u00e0 la cour\" In, ''Chasse-mar\u00e9e'' #228, 2010, pgs.60-65\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Th\u00e9odore Gudin}}\n* [http://www.artnet.com/artists/baron-jean-antoine-th\u00e9odore-gudin/ More works by Gudin] @ ArtNet\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gudin, Theodore}}\n\n[[Category:1802 births]]\n[[Category:1880 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Paris]]\n[[Category:19th-century French painters]]\n[[Category:French male painters]]\n[[Category:Peintres de la Marine]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pour le M\u00e9rite (civil class)]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Th%C3%A9odore_Gudin"}
{"title_page": "Sandro Cois", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Sandro Cois\n| image          = \n| height         = 1.78m\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|6|9}}\n| birth_place    = [[Fossano]], Italy\n| currentclub    = \n| position       = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| youthyears1    =           |youthclubs1   = [[Torino F.C.|Torino]]\n| years1         = 1988\u20131994 |clubs1 = [[Torino F.C.|Torino]]                 |caps1 = 44  |goals1 = 2\n| years2         = 1988\u20131989 |clubs2 = \u2192 [[Saviglianese]] (loan)              |caps2 = 18  |goals2 = 0\n| years3         = 1994\u20132002 |clubs3 = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]          |caps3 = 175 |goals3 = 7\n| years4         = 2002\u20132003 |clubs4 = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]           |caps4 = 4   |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2003      |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Piacenza Calcio|Piacenza]] (loan)  |caps5 = 5   |goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 246\n| totalgoals     = 9\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20131999 |nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] |nationalcaps1 = 3 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Sandro Cois''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8sandro \u02c8k\u0254is}}; born 9 June 1972) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|footballer]]. He enjoyed a lengthy career, playing primarily as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for Italian clubs [[Torino F.C.|Torino]], [[Saviglianese]], [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], and [[Piacenza Calcio|Piacenza]]. Due to his tactical intelligence, passing, stamina, tenacity, and versatility, he was capable of playing in several [[Midfielder|midfield]] and [[Defender (association football)|defensive]] positions.<ref name=\"L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solocalcio.com/FORZAVIOLA/Cois.htm|title=L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois|website=solocalcio.com|language=Italian|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> At international level, he represented [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on three occasions between 1998 and 1999, and was member of the team that took part at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\nCois was born in [[Fossano]]. He played for several clubs throughout his career, including [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] (1988\u20131994), [[UC Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] (2002\u201303) and [[Piacenza Calcio|Piacenza]] (2003). He achieved notable success with Torino early in his career, after achieving [[1990\u201391 Serie A|Serie A]] promotion by winning the [[1989\u201390 Serie B]] title with the club. He later won the [[Mitropa Cup]] in 1991, the [[Coppa Italia]] in 1993, and he helped his team to the [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup]] final, after helping his team to qualify for the tournament by leading them to a third place in Serie A in 1991. In the [[1992 UEFA Cup Final]], they were defeated by [[Ajax F.C.|Ajax]] on aggregate.<ref name=\"L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois\"/>\n\nCois is perhaps best known for his spell at [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] (1994\u20132002) in the mid-late 90s where he won over the fans with his tireless running and tenacious play, becoming important to the side as the less glamorous foil to playmakers like [[Rui Costa]] and [[Domenico Morfeo]]. With the club he won two [[Coppa Italia]] trophies in 1996 and 2001, and a [[Supercoppa Italiana]] in 1996, also helping Fiorentina to two third-place finishes in [[Serie A]] in [[1995\u201396 Serie A|1996]] and [[1998\u201399 Serie A|1999]].<ref name=\"L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1994/11/08/fiorentina-linea-verde.html|title=FIORENTINA LINEA VERDE|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=8 November 1994|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIt was during his period with Fiorentina in the late 90s that Cois broke into the [[Italy national football team]]. He was a participant at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], although he never became a regular in the side, winning just 3 caps between 1998 and 1999, one of which was in an unofficial match against the [[FIFA]] World Stars, also failing to make an appearance at the 1998 World Cup.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=1013/teams/team=43954.html 1998 FIFA World Cup: Italy Squad] ''[[FIFA]]''. Retrieved 22 January 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1119&squadra=1|title=Nazionale in cifre: Cois, Sandro|website=figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n\n====Club====\n'''Torino'''<ref name=eurosport.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/sandro-cois_prs4992/person.shtml|title=Sandro Cois|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Coppa Italia]]: [[1992\u201393 Coppa Italia|1992\u201393]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]]: Runner-up [[1994 Supercoppa Italiana|1994]]\n* [[Serie B]]: [[1989\u201390 Serie B|1989\u201390]]\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup|1991\u201392]]\n* [[Mitropa Cup]]: 1991\n* [[Memorial Pier Cesare Baretti]]: 1990, Runner-up 1993\n\n'''Fiorentina'''<ref name=eurosport.com/>\n* [[Coppa Italia]]: [[1995\u201396 Coppa Italia|1995\u201396]], [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|2000\u201301]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1996 Supercoppa Italiana|1996]]; Runner-up [[2001 Supercoppa Italiana|2001]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 1998 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cois, Sandro}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fossano]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Torino F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Piacenza Calcio 1919 players]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Italian people of Sardinian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Sandro Cois\n| image              = \n| height             = 1.78m\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|6|9}}\n| birth_place        = [[Fossano]], Italy\n| currentclub        = \n| position           = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| youthyears1        =           |youthclubs1   = [[Torino F.C.|Torino]]\n| years1             = 1988\u20131994 |clubs1        = [[Torino F.C.|Torino]]                 |caps1 = 44  |goals1 = 2\n| years2             = 1988\u20131989 |clubs2        = \u2192 [[Saviglianese]] (loan)              |caps2 = 18  |goals2 = 0\n| years3             = 1994\u20132002 |clubs3        = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]          |caps3 = 175 |goals3 = 7\n| years4             = 2002\u20132003 |clubs4        = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]           |caps4 = 4   |goals4 = 0\n| years5             = 2003      |clubs5        = \u2192 [[Piacenza Calcio|Piacenza]] (loan)  |caps5 = 5   |goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps          = 246\n| totalgoals         = 9\n| nationalyears1     = 1998\u20131999 |nationalteam1 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] |nationalcaps1 = 3 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Sandro Cois''' ({{IPA-it|\u02c8sandro \u02c8k\u0254is}}; born 9 June 1972) is a retired Italian [[Association football|footballer]]. He enjoyed a lengthy career, playing primarily as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for Italian clubs [[Torino F.C.|Torino]], [[Saviglianese]], [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], and [[Piacenza Calcio|Piacenza]]. Due to his tactical intelligence, passing, stamina, tenacity, and versatility, he was capable of playing in several [[Midfielder|midfield]] and [[Defender (association football)|defensive]] positions.<ref name=\"L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solocalcio.com/FORZAVIOLA/Cois.htm|title=L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois|website=solocalcio.com|language=Italian|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> At international level, he represented [[Italy national football team|Italy]] on three occasions between 1998 and 1999, and was member of the team that took part at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\nCois was born in [[Fossano]]. He played for several clubs throughout his career, including [[Torino F.C.|Torino]] (1988\u20131994), [[UC Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] (2002\u201303) and [[Piacenza Calcio|Piacenza]] (2003). He achieved notable success with Torino early in his career, after achieving [[1990\u201391 Serie A|Serie A]] promotion by winning the [[1989\u201390 Serie B]] title with the club. He later won the [[Mitropa Cup]] in 1991, the [[Coppa Italia]] in 1993, and he helped his team to the [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup]] final, after helping his team to qualify for the tournament by leading them to a third place in Serie A in 1991. In the [[1992 UEFA Cup Final]], they were defeated by [[Ajax F.C.|Ajax]] on aggregate.<ref name=\"L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois\"/>\n\nCois is perhaps best known for his spell at [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] (1994\u20132002) in the mid-late 90s where he won over the fans with his tireless running and tenacious play, becoming important to the side as the less glamorous foil to playmakers like [[Rui Costa]] and [[Domenico Morfeo]]. With the club he won two [[Coppa Italia]] trophies in 1996 and 2001, and a [[Supercoppa Italiana]] in 1996, also helping Fiorentina to two third-place finishes in [[Serie A]] in [[1995\u201396 Serie A|1996]] and [[1998\u201399 Serie A|1999]].<ref name=\"L'alfabeto di Sandro Cois\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1994/11/08/fiorentina-linea-verde.html|title=FIORENTINA LINEA VERDE|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=8 November 1994|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIt was during his period with Fiorentina in the late 90s that Cois broke into the [[Italy national football team]]. He was a participant at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], although he never became a regular in the side, winning just 3 caps between 1998 and 1999, one of which was in an unofficial match against the [[FIFA]] World Stars, also failing to make an appearance at the 1998 World Cup.<ref>[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=1013/teams/team=43954.html 1998 FIFA World Cup: Italy Squad] ''[[FIFA]]''. Retrieved 22 January 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato?codiceConvocato=1119&squadra=1|title=Nazionale in cifre: Cois, Sandro|website=figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=22 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Player===\n\n====Club====\n'''Torino'''<ref name=eurosport.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/sandro-cois_prs4992/person.shtml|title=Sandro Cois|publisher=Eurosport|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Coppa Italia]]: [[1992\u201393 Coppa Italia|1992\u201393]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]]: Runner-up [[1994 Supercoppa Italiana|1994]]\n* [[Serie B]]: [[1989\u201390 Serie B|1989\u201390]]\n* [[UEFA Cup]]: Runner-up [[1991\u201392 UEFA Cup|1991\u201392]]\n* [[Mitropa Cup]]: 1991\n* [[Memorial Pier Cesare Baretti]]: 1990, Runner-up 1993\n\n'''Fiorentina'''<ref name=eurosport.com/>\n* [[Coppa Italia]]: [[1995\u201396 Coppa Italia|1995\u201396]], [[2000\u201301 Coppa Italia|2000\u201301]]\n* [[Supercoppa Italiana]]: [[1996 Supercoppa Italiana|1996]]; Runner-up [[2001 Supercoppa Italiana|2001]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Italy Squad 1998 World Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cois, Sandro}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fossano]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:Torino F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Piacenza Calcio 1919 players]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina players]]\n[[Category:U.C. Sampdoria players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Italian people of Sardinian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tweaks.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandro_Cois"}
